#* {{quote-book|en|year=1866| title=Bracton and His Relation to the Roman Law|author=Karl Güterbock | page=164| passage=As in the Roman law the action was maintainable against the spoliator himself on the ground either of actual perpetration , or of instigation (besides that of ratihabitio); against the master in respect to his '''familia'''; and against all participants in the disseisin.}}
#* '''1875''', ''Classical pamphlets'', page 29:
#*: As Caesar tells us that the '''familia''' of the Helvetian leader, Orgetorix, numbered 10,000 persons, we can see that our word “family” has not the same meaning.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2012| title=The Empire of the Self|author=Christopher Star | page=240| passage=After declaring that “slaves are people too,” Trimalchio has a copy of his will read to prove that he will free them and so that his '''''familia''''' will love him as much now as when he is dead (71.1—5).}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2013| title=Atilus the Gladiator|author=E. C. Tubb | page= 21| passage=Unable to fight, he had gathered a troupe of gladiators and now moved around the provinces with his '''''familia'''''.}}
# {{rfv-sense|en}} A quantity of land adequate for the maintenance of one family.
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1861|month-April|work=National Review |title=Mr. Maine on Ancient Law|author=|volume=12|number=24|passage= The first step towards the establishment of individual rights was on the death of the patriarch for his '''''familia''''' to pass not to the eldest son, but to all the children; these took the succession as a single person, and then by a subsequent process divided the property equally and each set up a '''''familia''''' for himself.}}

